# Analysis I mathematics still to be completed
#
# This is a comment-only ledger.  It is not a chapter, is not exported by
# litex.config, and contains no executable Litex declarations.
#
# Snapshot: 2026-07-21.  The book currently contains 68 direct `trust` sites,
# all in Chapters 5, 7, 8, 9, and 11.  Chapters 1-4, 6, and 10, together with
# Appendix A, contain no direct `trust` statement.
#
# Each item names the theorem whose proof contains the hole, gives the current
# source line for quick lookup, states the missing mathematics, and says which
# source-facing result the hole supports.  Line numbers are secondary locators
# and may move as chapters are edited.
#
# Chapter 5 — The real numbers (2 direct trust sites)
#
# Item 05-01 — Section 5.3; cauchy_sequence_representative_in_Q_exists.
# Current location: chapter05-real-numbers.lit, line 593.
# Missing mathematics: construct, for every builtin real number, a rational
# Cauchy sequence representing it and prove that the sequence has that formal
# real limit.  This compatibility statement is not a separate theorem in the
# source, because the source defines real numbers by the Cauchy construction.
# It serves the bridge between the source construction of R and Litex's builtin
# real-number carrier.
#
# Item 05-02 — Section 5.5; real_cauchy_sequence_has_limit_in_R.
# Current location: chapter05-real-numbers.lit, line 2204.
# Missing mathematics: prove sequential completeness of the builtin real
# numbers from the rational-Cauchy construction.
# It serves the bisection and least-upper-bound development later in Section
# 5.5.  The source obtains this from its construction of the real numbers, so
# Litex needs an explicit compatibility proof that the builtin carrier lacks.
#
# Chapter 7 — Series (12 direct trust sites)
#
# Item 07-01 — Section 7.2; alternating_series_tail_bound.
# Current location: chapter07-series.lit, line 1726.
# Missing mathematics: prove by induction and parity that every finite tail of
# a decreasing non-negative alternating sequence is bounded in absolute value
# by its first available term.
# It supplies the decisive tail estimate for the alternating series test.  The
# source proof marks several induction and parity steps as "why?".
#
# Item 07-02 — Section 7.2; alternating_series_test_reverse.
# Current location: chapter07-series.lit, line 1854.
# Missing mathematics: prove that the harmonic series diverges.
# It is used to show that the alternating harmonic series is conditionally,
# rather than absolutely, convergent.  The source routes this through the
# p-series criterion whose final comparison is left as a "why?" step.
#
# Item 07-03 — Section 7.3; p_series_converges_when_exponent_gt_one.
# Current location: chapter07-series.lit, line 2992.
# Missing mathematics: complete Cauchy condensation and the equivalence
# abs(2^(1-q)) < 1 exactly when q > 1.
# It supplies the convergent half of Corollary 7.3.7, the p-series criterion;
# the source leaves the final exponent comparison as "why?".
#
# Item 07-04 — Section 7.3; p_series_diverges_when_exponent_le_one.
# Current location: chapter07-series.lit, line 2999.
# Missing mathematics: prove the divergent half of the condensed geometric
# series comparison when q <= 1.
# It completes Corollary 7.3.7 and also supports the harmonic-series
# divergence used in the alternating-harmonic example.
#
# Item 07-05 — Section 7.4; rearranged_partial_sum_le_original_at_bounded_prefix.
# Current location: chapter07-series.lit, line 3182.
# Missing mathematics: reindex a finite non-negative sum and show that a
# rearranged prefix is bounded by an original prefix containing its image.
# It is one half of the cofinal-partial-sum argument for Proposition 7.4.1 on
# rearrangements of convergent non-negative series.
#
# Item 07-06 — Section 7.4; original_partial_sum_le_rearranged_at_bounded_preimage.
# Current location: chapter07-series.lit, line 3191.
# Missing mathematics: reindex the finite sum in the reverse direction and
# bound an original prefix by a rearranged prefix containing all preimages.
# It is the second half of the cofinal-partial-sum argument for Proposition
# 7.4.1.
#
# Item 07-07 — Section 7.4; nonnegative_series_same_sum_from_cofinal_partial_sums.
# Current location: chapter07-series.lit, line 3227.
# Missing mathematics: prove that two non-negative series with mutually
# cofinal partial sums have the same limit.
# It converts the two finite-prefix comparisons into the sum-preservation
